456
00:48:14,747 --> 00:48:17,368
[SPEAKER_05]: What I wanted to point out and I think we mentioned in the letter, right?

457
00:48:17,388 --> 00:48:22,669
[SPEAKER_05]: We've got what we'll do and we always do is contract with a snow removal company, right?

458
00:48:22,729 --> 00:48:27,750
[SPEAKER_05]: It's not Mill Creek will have a third party who is hired to handle snow removal.

459
00:48:28,230 --> 00:48:35,491
[SPEAKER_05]: A lot of our communities, we have big parking areas that require a lot of thinking about where snow storage can occur.

460
00:48:35,511 --> 00:48:37,912
[SPEAKER_05]: You know, one of the

461
00:48:39,446 --> 00:48:49,372
[SPEAKER_05]: You know, benefits of having all the parking in a garage here in our in our covered enclosed garages is that we really don't have that much plowable area if you will.

462
00:48:51,033 --> 00:48:56,456
[SPEAKER_05]: So, our, our thinking and our plan is that for, you know, sort of routine snow events.

463
00:48:56,916 --> 00:49:01,859
[SPEAKER_05]: There is enough wiggle room area in either landscape areas or.

464
00:49:05,078 --> 00:49:10,519
[SPEAKER_05]: or in our buffer area that we can handle a routine storm without having to take snow off site.

465
00:49:11,379 --> 00:49:22,101
[SPEAKER_05]: However, part of our contract, and we do this elsewhere, is that in a larger storm event, it's our snow removal contractor's responsibility to get that snow off site.

466
00:49:22,321 --> 00:49:29,862
[SPEAKER_05]: They can't pile it up in a way that it impedes pedestrian traffic or certainly vehicular traffic, emergency vehicle, et cetera.

467
00:49:30,703 --> 00:49:32,443
[SPEAKER_05]: So that's really, again, more of an

468
00:49:36,170 --> 00:49:39,033
[SPEAKER_05]: but above a certain amount of snow, that's got to go offsite.

469
00:49:41,555 --> 00:49:45,198
[SPEAKER_13]: Tim, I'd caution you, you don't have very much wiggle area.

470
00:49:46,559 --> 00:49:46,979
[SPEAKER_05]: Understood.

471
00:49:47,700 --> 00:49:48,100
[SPEAKER_05]: Understood.

472
00:49:48,400 --> 00:49:53,304
[SPEAKER_05]: And I think that probably dictates the contract as well, Mr. Reardon, I appreciate that.

473
00:49:56,027 --> 00:49:57,428
[SPEAKER_13]: Heated pavement's an option too.

474
00:49:58,609 --> 00:49:59,109
[SPEAKER_03]: I'm sorry?

475
00:49:59,670 --> 00:50:01,071
[SPEAKER_13]: Heated pavement's an option too.

476
00:50:05,691 --> 00:50:22,159
[SPEAKER_14]: So to that point, though, I guess, how do we kind of get to a confidence level around how much space is or isn't enough, right?

477
00:50:22,179 --> 00:50:29,362
[SPEAKER_14]: This applies both to the space to clear snow as well as the space for

478
00:50:31,772 --> 00:50:35,135
[SPEAKER_14]: Uber Eats and so on and move-in vehicles.

479
00:50:35,395 --> 00:50:43,941
[SPEAKER_14]: So it sounds like the scheduling will address the issue with multiple move-in vehicles at one time.

480
00:50:44,022 --> 00:50:59,994
[SPEAKER_14]: But yeah, is there a standard way to actually do the back of the envelope math to establish this is or isn't enough space to do what's being proposed?

481
00:51:01,044 --> 00:51:08,709
[SPEAKER_13]: Well, to answer that question, as far as snow goes, yeah, there's a pretty easy way to sort of do a calculation of how much snow you can store.

482
00:51:09,210 --> 00:51:16,374
[SPEAKER_13]: But I can tell you, based on what they have and the layout of the sidewalks and the layout of the landscape, there is no storage area.

483
00:51:16,675 --> 00:51:23,179
[SPEAKER_13]: So you literally couldn't plow a 20-foot wide roadway with the space that you have on either side.

484
00:51:23,727 --> 00:51:31,390
[SPEAKER_13]: So I think to Tim's point, you're looking at a snow management that involves immediate removal from the site.

485
00:51:32,030 --> 00:51:45,215
[SPEAKER_13]: That's not impossible, but what it needs to be done is documented as part of a baseline expectation that the board has so that we're not getting into a situation where they do try to plow it and you get into a problem with your

486
00:51:45,915 --> 00:51:54,807
[SPEAKER_13]: the court to the sheet north or whether it's encumbering sidewalks continually or encumbering the area that's dedicated for fire access.

487
00:51:54,888 --> 00:52:02,238
[SPEAKER_13]: So as part of this process, we see our role as being identifying where these sort of constraints on the site

488
00:52:03,130 --> 00:52:13,261
[SPEAKER_13]: are likely to manifest themselves as problems going forward and get as much clarity as part of this process and as clear a condition as possible in any decision.

489
00:52:13,361 --> 00:52:23,693
[SPEAKER_13]: So yeah, I think the next step is, as Tim said, is they've got to sort of elevate the plan a little bit, give a little bit of description on how they plan on using it.

490
00:52:25,832 --> 00:52:30,334
[SPEAKER_13]: we've got to give them the benefit of at least proposing a solution, and then we'll comment accordingly.

491
00:52:30,354 --> 00:52:37,937
[SPEAKER_13]: And if we think it's undersized, or if we think it encroaches on access needed for the emergency vehicles, then we'll comment as such.

492
00:52:37,957 --> 00:52:40,718
[SPEAKER_14]: Okay, thank you, Mr. Reardon.

